== Dangerous, Forbidden & Hunted Magic

A relationship based on fear of being hurt by the magic, fear of the consequences of being discovered, and the risk of letting someone close enough to see what you really are is automatically filled with built-in romantic tension.

To write dangerous magic well, you should demonstrate your character's physical awareness of their power at all times. The way they hold themselves still. The reflexive clenching when emotions spike. The careful distance they maintain. Show the reader how many near-misses have happened: the glass that cracks, the temperature drop, the flicker of something wrong that the character quickly suppresses.

In Shatter Me, Juliette's lethal touch means she can kill anyone who makes skin contact. The entire romance is built on the question of who can survive touching her, and what it means when someone can. The tension builds as the partner moves closer while the dangerous one backs away. When the dangerous character finally allows the partner to touch them during a moment of extreme emotion, this is a pivotal moment in the story. They're choosing trust over safety.

